                        <div class="people-card-grid-modal-right">
                            <h3>Rebecca Buller</h3>
                            <h5></h5>
                            <p class="bio">Dr. Rebecca A. Buller is a cultural and historical geographer at the University of Nebraska—Lincoln, where she is an associate professor of practice in the School of Global Integrative Studies-Geography Program. She is also a fellow and journals’ book review editor at the Center for Great Plains Studies. Her scholarly activities focus on the Great Plains, American West, Iceland, genders’ studies, geographic inquiry, experiential education, and human trafficking. Current achievements include the creation and leading of new classes, like “Environmental Justice” and “Geography Field Tour: Iceland: People, Landscapes, and Sustainability in the Land of Fire and Ice,” a grant to help fund the co-investigation of COVID-19 Stories “Journal of a Plague Year” | “Birth and Early Infant Feeding Experiences of Mothers,” and the essay “Re-envisioning a Visioned Landscape” in <em>Field Guide to a Hybrid Landscape</em> (Fritz et al. 2023). She is a seven-time award recipient of the UNL Parents’ Association &#8220;Certificate of Recognition for Contributions to Students.” Dr. Buller holds degrees in Geography and History Secondary Education (B.S.Ed.) and Historical and Cultural Geography (M.A., Ph.D.) from the University of Nebraska—Lincoln. She is also certified in Red Cross cardiopulmonary resuscitation and automated external defibrillator (CPR/AED) for Professional Rescuers with First Aid and Wilderness First Aid (WFA) for first responders. Her service as GPRM Councilor will run through 2026.</p>
