                                                            <img decoding="async" class="headshot" src="https://www.aag.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/Steven-Silvern-8-23.jpg" alt="Photo of Steven Silvern" loading="lazy">
                                                        <ul class="people-card-grid-social-links">
                                                                                                                                    <li class="email"><a href="mailto:ssilvern@salemstate.edu"><?xml version="1.0" ?><svg class="icon" style="enable-background:new 0 0 24 24;" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 24 24" xml:space="preserve" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g id="info"/><g id="icons"><path d="M20,3H4C1.8,3,0,4.8,0,7v10c0,2.2,1.8,4,4,4h16c2.2,0,4-1.8,4-4V7C24,4.8,22.2,3,20,3z M21.6,8.8l-7.9,5.3   c-0.5,0.3-1.1,0.5-1.7,0.5s-1.2-0.2-1.7-0.5L2.4,8.8C2,8.5,1.9,7.9,2.2,7.4C2.5,7,3.1,6.9,3.6,7.2l7.9,5.3c0.3,0.2,0.8,0.2,1.1,0   l7.9-5.3c0.5-0.3,1.1-0.2,1.4,0.3C22.1,7.9,22,8.5,21.6,8.8z" id="email"/></g></svg></a></li>
                                                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div class="people-card-grid-modal-right">
                            <h3>Steven E. Silvern</h3>
                            <h5></h5>
                            <p class="bio">He is professor of geography in the Department of Geography and Sustainability at Salem State University. His research focuses on the political geographies of Native Americans, the changing local geography of food systems and faith-based climate and environmental activism. His research has appeared in <em>Cultural Geographies</em>, <em>Political Geography</em>, <em>Historical Geography</em>, and <em>American Indian Culture and Research Journal</em>. His most recent work is a co-edited volume (with Edward Davis) entitled Religion, Sustainability and Place: Moral Geographies of the Anthropocene (Palgrave Mcmillan, 2021). He served as the editor of <em>The Northeastern Geography</em>, the NESTVAL annual journal from 2009 until 2022. In 2020, he was awarded Nestval&#8217;s Distinguished Service Award. Dr. Silvern holds a B.A. from Clark University, a M.S. from the University of Illinois and a Ph.D. from the University of Wisconsin-Madison. His service as NESTVAL Regional Councilor will run through June 2025.</p>
                                                                                </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                        
                <div class="people-card-grid-item" data-modal="people-card-grid-modal-8943">
                    <div class="people-card-grid-item-inner">
                                                    <img decoding="async" src="https://www.aag.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Heidi-Lannon.jpg" alt="PHoto of Heidi Lannon" loading="lazy">
                                                <h5 class="name">Heidi Lannon</h5>
                        <h6 class="title">Southeast</h6>
                        <p class="tagline"></p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="people-card-grid-modal-modal-content">
                        <div class="people-card-grid-modal-left">
                                                            <img decoding="async" class="headshot" src="https://www.aag.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Heidi-Lannon.jpg" alt="PHoto of Heidi Lannon" loading="lazy">
                                                        <ul class="people-card-grid-social-links">
                                                                                                                                    <li class="email"><a href="mailto:heidi.lannon@sfcollege.edu"><?xml version="1.0" ?><svg class="icon" style="enable-background:new 0 0 24 24;" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 24 24" xml:space="preserve" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"><g id="info"/><g id="icons"><path d="M20,3H4C1.8,3,0,4.8,0,7v10c0,2.2,1.8,4,4,4h16c2.2,0,4-1.8,4-4V7C24,4.8,22.2,3,20,3z M21.6,8.8l-7.9,5.3   c-0.5,0.3-1.1,0.5-1.7,0.5s-1.2-0.2-1.7-0.5L2.4,8.8C2,8.5,1.9,7.9,2.2,7.4C2.5,7,3.1,6.9,3.6,7.2l7.9,5.3c0.3,0.2,0.8,0.2,1.1,0   l7.9-5.3c0.5-0.3,1.1-0.2,1.4,0.3C22.1,7.9,22,8.5,21.6,8.8z" id="email"/></g></svg></a></li>
                                                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div class="people-card-grid-modal-right">
                            <h3>Heidi Lannon</h3>
                            <h5></h5>
                            <p class="bio">Heidi Lannon’s background is as a physical geographer specializing in coastal geomorphology, and she is the past chair of the Coastal and Marine AAG specialty group. Her research focuses predominantly recruitment into, and promotion of Geography, particularly for underrepresented groups, and geographic education and the relevance of field work. She has written on the status of women in Geography in <em>Southeastern Geographer</em> and is the past chair of the SEDAAG Inclusive, Diverse, Equitable and Accessible in Learning (IDEAL) Geographer committee. She returns after a year in a visiting position at Kings College London specializing in natural hazards and fieldwork, to her former role as a professor of Geography at Santa Fe College in Gainesville Florida, and as an adjunct professor at the University of Florida. She hopes to continue transatlantic collaborations with British Geographers. She holds a PhD in Geography from the University of Florida, Masters of Public Administration, and Coastal Management from the University of West Florida, and a BSc, Hons., in Environmental Science from the University of Ulster. She holds American Association of Certified Planners credentials. Her service as the Southeast Division Regional Councilor will run through 2026.</p>
                                                                                </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                    </div>
    </div>
    
